title: For Sale:  WANT TO BUY!! BEWARE!!  I GOT SCAMMED!!  READ ON...
postcontent:
I recently got scammed buy a guy here on Armslist who called himself Mark Lerner.  He said he had some Pmags I had put up as "want to buy".  He said he had 11 of them and gave me agreat deal on 5 of them.  He asked I send money thru moneygram and include delivery.  With much back and forth in my own mind I went against my gut and decide to trust this guy. He told me numerous time in his poorly spelled texts(red flag) that I didnt need to worry and that I would get them as soon as I made a payment.  I paid for them and 2 days later he sent me a Fedex delivery conformation email that looked real except it had no tracking number. I called Fedex and there was no record of a package being delivered to my residence.  When I confronted "Mark" he said he'd call Fedex.  When he got back to me he said "ATF was holding my package and I needed to pay them $150.00 for them to deliver my package."  He said the ATF told him it was a "safe handling fee".  I told him I didn't Obelieve him anymore and requested him to send me pics of the Pmags... He downloaded, probably from google image, a pic of the wrong Pmag and sent it to me.  Obviously I didn't pay this fucker any more money... Luckily wasn't buying a $1200 gun either...  PLEASE BEWARE!! I'd hate for this to happen to someone else!  

If you want any info about this asshole contact me.

title: For Sale/Trade:  BNZ 1941 Mauser 98k
postcontent: Hey guys Ive got a really nice BNZ 41 mauser 98k that is in superb condition with no import stamp(possible vet bring back), but its mismatched. The barrel, action, and sights match themselves, the bolt completely matches itself, and the stock matches itself(except for the buttplate, I believe that this is a Norwegian capture). The correct Waffenamts are on the rifle, which includes WaA623 on the barrel, action, front sight, floorplate and stock; and WaA77 on the barrel bands, rear sight, and bolt(I believe this rifle was redone by the Radom plant in Poland that was owned and operated by BNZ in Steyr). Furthermore, there is not a Waffenamt on the receiver above the BNZ code, which means that this was not regular army issue. The bore is in pristine condition with strong lands and grooves, and about 90% of the bluing is in tact on the rifle with some rubbed off under the front barrel band and the sight hood. Rifle comes with a sling and cleaning rod. Price is 1000 OBO(these matching go for about 3000+ in bad condition). For trades, I will take a PTR-91, an East German Walther ppk with some ammo, or an FAL. I think I have about 20 or so rounds for this. Thanks for your time and have a great day. If you need more pictures, dont hesitate to ask. You can contact me by phone at six-zero-one-four-seven-nine-three-three-five-six

title: For Trade:  I appreciate a little heads up
postcontent:
Since armslist classified is now a forum to air out grievances along with selling guns sometimes, I want to throw in my two cents.
I appreciate when someone points out sales on items online that may turn up here.
I like it when someone points out that there are mismatched or improperly "custom built" ARs out there that may turn up here.
I like to know when Palmetto State or other companies are selling blems for nothing and people are selling them here for retail
Its a good thing when someone lists retail stores that aren't screwing people on .22LR ammo so that we have a chance to buy some before the douche bag resellers get it in the north state.
I like it when folks call out douche bags reselling .22LR and flags them.
Now, if someone is dumb enough to buy a rifle in the parking lot of BILO having not done any homework on it, thats on them. If you've gotta have a gun that bad, you probably don't need it or you probably aren't allowed to own it.
There are plenty of sites to get a handle on what things should sell for: buds, jgsales, centerfiresystems are just a few. Anyone that will pay $1200 for a rifle that is sold for $799 is more than likely a person who can't buy one through the proper channels. Anyone who is listing a rifle for that is fishing for a fool or trying to sell to criminals who can't use the proper channels.
Either way, I have it from pretty good sources that most of the frequent "reselling" activities here are being monitored so in the end you may likely just be screwing yourself if you are acting like a weekend gun dealer without an FFL.

title: For Trade:  Let's Talk Magazines
postcontent:
I am a retired Navy Chief (1985-2007) and while on active duty completed eight combat tours.  During these tours I carried 1911, Glock, and BHP model pistols--I was also a RMSO for small arms qualifications.  I will never claim to be an expert on anything (I believe self-described experts are educated idiots) but nonetheless know a thing or two about firearms.

I have owned several different 1911 models, from low-end entry level guns to some of the more expensive.  One thing that has always pissed me off is these so called "experts" that say all 1911 mags are interchangeable.  THEY'RE NOT!!!  You may get a Ruger SR1911 to accept a R100 mag and it may even feed flawlessly, but then it won't lock the slide back after the last round.  I've even had "experts" tell me all I have to do is tweak the lips--it'll work fine then.  Bullshit.  This is not proper firearm maintenance and upkeep.

So, I was wondering.  With the variety of mag lips available--GI, Wadcutter, Hybrid, etc. has anyone begun a chart or tracking which model guns work well or better with other model guns' magazines?  Thoughts?  Comments?  Even the McCormick mags are not 100 percent reliable across the board.

This new 30-30 load was designed as the single 30-30 load for all big game hunting. The Barnes TSX opens fast enough to be brutal on deer sized critters, yet penetrates like TSX bullets normally do, so it gives ample penetration for larger species such as elk. While we feel the 30-30 is marginal for big bull elk, this is the load to use if you choose to pursue elk with a 30-30 and then use the same load to hunt deer, so you don’t have to readjust your sights for differing loads. This is the perfect load to hunt black bear of all sizes with as the bullet will expand fast enough to deliver terminal devastation on smallish bear, but will penetrate deeply enough for 500+ lb bear.
